They will have access to not only your medical history, but also your physical self and will therefore be in a better position than ourselves to make a full assessment of any symptoms you are experiencing.
> 
> Here are comments from our resident doctor regarding your results:
> 
> The HbA1c level (a test for levels of glucose in the blood over the preceding weeks) is above the threshold for the diagnosis of diabetes mellitus. The cut off level is 48 mmol/mol according to the World Health Organisation guidelines â yours is 58. The implication of this result is that you are likely to have diabetes, or at least impaired glucose tolerance or insulin resistance. I advise you to discuss this result with your usual doctor at your earliest convenience, especially if you do not yet have a diagnosis of diabetes.
> 
> There is Vitamin D insufficiency. Vitamin D is manufactured in our skin as a direct result of sunlight exposure. One potential complication of prolonged Vitamin D lack is osteomalacia, a disease which causes severe structural deformities to the skeleton. Lower level Vitamin D deficiency can lead to a number of non-specific symptoms, including possibly chronic fatigue (experts have for many years noted an association between sufferers of chronic fatigue syndrome or myalgic encephalitis (CFS or ME) and low blood levels of Vitamin D). It has been estimated that between 50-70% of people living in the more northern reaches of the northern hemisphere (where daylight length reduces your chances of receiving adequate sunlight in the winter) are deficient in this vitamin by March each year. Symptoms of vitamin D deficiency include chronic pain, weak bones, frequent infections (recent research has detected an association between vitamin D deficiency and severe pneumonia), depression and fatigue. Supplementation may be beneficial.
> 
> The neutrophil count (and therefore the percentage variation of the total white cell count) is reduced (neutropenia). Neutrophils are among the body's first lines of defence against infection, and will rise, and later possibly fall, in number whenever the body is fighting infection - in these circumstances of course it is an appropriate response. Persistently low levels may indicate a deficiency in the immune system, and further investigation would be advisable if this was the case. It would be reasonable to run the test again in 4 weeks or so.
> 
> Having a high level of high density lipoprotein (HDL) level is good news, and is associated with a lower lifetime risk of developing cardiovascular (heart and blood vessel) disease. The 'HDL % of total figure' is probably the better guide to primary risk from cholesterol (i.e. the risk from cholesterol alone, if there is no established heart disease, high blood pressure or diabetes for example) â at 64%, your lifetime risk of developing heart disease from cholesterol induced damage alone is likely to be low. Your absolute risk of developing heart and vascular disease is dependent on a number of factors including weight, blood pressure, whether you smoke or are diabetic or not, and family history.
>

> 
> Many thanks,
